In article <16FC9FF5CS86.C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu>, C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu writes:
>In article <CqMsMy.1po@ulysses.homer.att.com>
>smb@research.att.com (Steven Bellovin) writes:
> 
>>If you're trying to do something MD5-like, by using a constant key,
>>the scheme I suggested above doesn't work.  You can build a hash function
>>from DES, but it's more complex.
> 
>   In Eurocrypt '92 (I think), there was an article by Massey and Lai,
>describing several methods for building strong hash functions out of
>block ciphers, as well as several attacks against them.
> 
>   It's called something like _Hash Functions from Block Ciphers_.

Yes, these are very interesting schemes, but unfortunately
most of them require the use of a 64-bit block cipher with
a 128-bit key (like IDEA), so DES cannot be used. The full
reference is:

 Xuejia Lai and James L. Massey,
 "Hash Functions Based on Block Ciphers",
 pp 55-70,
 Lecture Notes in Computer Science 658,
 Advances in Cryptology - EUROCRYPT '92.


> --John Kelsey, c445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu

